notes.note:
Hey Danielle, I am surprised that they are surprised. It is not every day a valve cover cracks. It is a very rare occurrence here at the claims desk, hence the additional questions and inquiries. That being said, I spoke with my claims manager and he would like me to proceed with the claim for you. Fortunately the timing cover gasket replacement and left side valve cover replacement are both covered. Unfortunately we will not be able to proceed with the claim for the pinion seal as the pictures provided do not show a leak. As previously mentioned, the engine oil cooler and oil pressure sensor are not covered, and neither is the differential flush and air filter replacement.

Please be advised, the customer is responsible for any diagnostic fees, nuts and bolts for timing cover (not covered), fluids, and shop supplies, as well as a $100 deductible + tax. Additionally, the customer's contract covers them for a maximum of $130/h for labour. If you choose to charge the quoted labour time of $199.95/h, the customer will be responsible for the difference. The payout is as follows:

Parts-$990.62
Labour-$2171.00 (16.7 hours x $130/h)
Deductible-$100.00
Tax-$158.08
Authorization-CEPV7CGMX6

Total = $3219.70

Once the repair is complete, please send us a copy of the final invoice for payment.

Best regards,

Our labour rate is $179.95+tax – I the estimate I accounted for 1 hour of remove and replace as advised by my supervisor with an additional 0.7 for diagnostic time that our technician has done to find the issue. We also use pro demand to have our time estimates – we just know from experience that it isn’t sufficient time for our technicians to complete the work so we have adjusted to 1. That brings us to a total of 1.7hours x $179.95 = $305.92+tax



I apologize for the odometer reading – I remember you mentioning it to me. Here it is: 129 013



Let me know if you need anything else! Thank you.



Take care,

Alexandre Richardson

Service Advisor
